However, trade is controlled and processed by a central authority every time.
With Bitcoin, all network notes are simultaneously stored by accounts, auditors, money issuers, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users takes place in reality between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A series of data related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the trading Bitcoins are available in the public accounts book distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This happens through a mathematical task that starts on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of temporary central banker, having the privilege to add these additional lines.
This is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprints.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that produces a special fingerprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
When this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay twice very fast (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other remains unlinked as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 Bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The Bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but shared to a hundred million sets, allowing a certain gambling space.
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement in calculation performance.
