End of the UNAUR Summit without the publication of the Lima Declaration
The sixth summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Declaration of Lima, which was previously announced and should be signed theoretically by the seven present governments.
Efe attempted repeatedly to obtain access to the signed document at the VIth Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of the Unasur. Sources at the National and Presidency Office initially reported that they would be transferred to it after the clause, but afterwards declared that it would be published on the Peruvian Government website for some time.
When asked questions about the text, they stated that the content was submitted to the press by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements.
The access of journalists to information about the summit was limited at any time.
During the day, only the image of the presidential meeting was transmitted in the press room without sound with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulated among journalists were received by the press speakers of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press speaker.
The only document that was published during the day was the list of the participating presidents, which encouraged hundreds of journalists of various national and international media uncomfortable demanding more information.
The President of Peru then sent the media an e-mail with the “concluding statement” of the summit, but it was the statement of Humala and not the official document for the completion of the summit.
Last October, Peru was host of the third summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and also at this opportunity, despite a press press call, Lima’s so-called statement previously announced was just as little published.
On the official website of ASPA you can be convinced that the document was published on Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities emphasized that information systems would be available for journalists, but they restricted high level access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru, to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of the Hague that joins a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would adopt the decision of the Court initiating Monday in the Hague in the process of launching Lima against Santiago to listen to both sides.
"We will follow, follow and execute the judgment on the differences we are making to this international court right now," Humala said along with his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile was, is and remains a country that follows international laws, seeks peaceful dispute resolutions, concludes agreements and undertakes international courts,” said Piñera, greeting Humala with a hand pressure in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of both Presidents that they would be subjected to the Court of Justice took place after Colombia, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which considered it a serious mistake, raised a complaint against the Bogotá Agreement, which agreed to submit to the judgments of the International Court.
At the summit, the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from the Unasur since 2011 after his President Fernando Lugo was dismissed, has not participated in the meeting.
Hosting President Ollanta Humala opened the conversations in the morning and ended the summit shortly after the lunchtime in Lima.
The head of state laid down the final document, which reported that 16 decisions were made and the action lines for 31 projects between the South American countries were set over an investment amount of a total of $17 billion.
Among the decisions taken, he said that the Unasur countries will "take significant steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship, which will extend us to the decisions on residence rights."
He stated that measures would be promoted to improve cooperation in the fight against uncertainty in cities and against organized cross-country crimes, as well as to improve access to drugs and Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act together and effectively in the event of natural disasters.
With the crisis in Europe, “the economic consolidation (in Latin America) should not adopt triumphable trains, but should serve to expand our production performance and show our people a better future,” Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a series of 31 emblematic projects to improve spatial connections in South America and especially in rural and border areas... and thus unite our countries and create new economic forms," the President of Peru said in a statement.
Among these projects were five Peruvians located on the cross-border axis of their territory from the coast to Brazil, two of which should ensure a better connection with Ecuador although he did not give any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the election process in this country will serve for its reintegration into the Union of South American nations," which is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbouring relations was another aspect that was emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos, before he began his participation in the regional meeting, said that he was expecting a meeting with his opponent to Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday to treat the maritime conflict with respect after a judgment of the IGH in question by Bogotá.
"I may meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and the deal with Nicaragua is also necessary for negotiations with Nicaragua," he said.
"I hope to be able to tell the President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectfully as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the office of the new president of the country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the Defence Ministers of the Block also met in advance to adopt the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, even though the last country is currently excluded.
